column1: The secrets behind Toowoomba’s ‘deliberately restrained’ theatre
column5: Passers-by could easily miss the work of Paul Chrismas and Mark Tendys. Tucked behind the Empire Church Theatre, and right next door to the famous art deco Empire Theatre, is a simple concrete and glass structure. Mr Tendys says he wanted his building to give prominence to what was already on the site. "It was a conscious design decision. We never set out to try and mimic either of the two existing theatres," he said.

column1: Ride to work (every) day
column5: John Hughes rides 19 kilometres each way to work, including several impressive hills through Toowoomba. "I don't mind it," he said. "I grew up in Brisbane where there was a lot more traffic. You don't think about work, you concentrate on the ride and it's a good mental exercise as well as a physical one." Mr Hughes says bike commuters do need to be organised. "There are a few logistic challenges. I take my clothes and food into work on the weekend. But my car doesn't sit outside in the sun all day and I get to enjoy the fresh air five days a week."

column1: Indigenous youth mourn past but look to future

column1: Retiring church singers share their 'secret' rock star story
column5: Music has played a major part in the lives of (l-r) Ruth Greenwood, Joan Thurrowgood, and her husband Arthur Thurrowgood. The three performed as the Joytones during the 1960s, playing to audiences all over the world. "We realise some people have no idea of what we used to do," Joan said. The days of playing as a self described '60s guitar group' are long behind them, but they have, up until now, kept playing music in their local church. "I'm silver haired now," Joan explained. "And I often wonder what the young people think when we're up on the platform. Do they say to themselves, 'what are those old people doing up there'. They don't know our history."

column1: Behind the screens at the Vision Splendid Outback Film Festival
column5: The Royal Open Air Theatre in Winton has been in Peter Evert’s family since 1938. He’s allowed the theatre to be used for the Vision Splendid Outback Film Festival and says he is delighted the historic building is being given another chance at life. Mr Evert says he believes the festival could one day compare to the Sundance Film Festival in the United States. “That’s evolved into a unique form of festival, and this could do that, concentrating on Australian movies rather than international ones and build up from there. column1: Don't forget the D-Day sacrifice
column5: Reg Jones keeps an album of photos he took during the war years. He reminisces as he looks at a photo of himself when he first enlisted. "This young Reg didn't know what he was in for," he said. "I thought it'd all be over in six months." Mr Jones suffered a broken back from a bomb blast during the Battle of Britain, which meant he wasn't part of the fighting units that landed on French soil on June 6, 1944. He was later transferred to MI5 to serve in Germany after the war. "We were the spy catchers. I could tell you lots of stories, but I signed the official secrets act to make sure I didn't talk about it. But I've still got the memories."

column1: Momenta Monumenta
column5: "I've always been interested in how things don't last, and using a camera for moments of history," says Emilio Cresciani. "Tips are full of objects that have been used. I've inverted them as a negative. The negative consequence of our lifestyle is the rubbish. They kind of remind me as x-rays. We are constantly consuming and buying. Things don't last in this world. It could either be because we lose them, technology changes, or because they wear out. That fascinates me."

column1: Remembering the Rats of Tobruk
column5: Rat of Tobruk Henry Tranter from Millaa Millaa in the Atherton Tablelands is now 96 years old and made the journey south to be part of the ceremony with his daughter Mary Jane Salleras. Mr Tranter was a signaller during the Siege of Tobruk. He said there was no way they could have known back then how important their part would be during the war. “The general said when the siege first started, here there’ll be no surrender and no retreat so we knew we were there to stay.”

column1: Would you cop it?
column5: Queensland Police are in the midst of a recruitment drive around the state. Inspector Mark Henderson from the Longreach Police says this South Australian police poster from 1838 shows how much has changed since those early recruitment days. “They really only looked for men. They looked for men who could ride horses, they looked for men who could fight, you had to be a certain height, a certain weight, and really not a lot else went into it. Now we are obviously in a community and we represent and police a community that’s multifaceted, multidimensional and multicultural.”

column1: Vivid memories of Spring Bluff march 72 years on
column5: At the time the soldiers had no idea where they were going. They boarded a train to Brisbane, and then travelled to New Guinea, where they would go on to win one of the most significant battles of WW2, the Battle of Milne Bay. Each year, the anniversary of the march is commemorated with a memorial service at the station. This year, there are only two surviving members of the 1000 strong battalion that made the trip; Bert Miles and Kevin Olsen.

column1: Shandee Blackburn: memories of an angel
column5: For Shandee's mother, Vicki Blackburn, there are too many happy memories of her baby girl. “My first and probably happiest memory was when she was born. She nearly didn’t make it, I had an emergency ceasar. We rushed in and then I had a reaction to the epidural and then I woke up after surgery and I didn’t know if she’d made it or not. I said to my husband, 'where’s the baby?' and he said, 'she’s looking at you.' And they had her in my arms and she was just laying there looking at me. That was sweet. She had strawberry blonde hair, just that blonde hair with that tinge of pink in it so I thought, here’s trouble.”

column1: A legend through the lens
column5: "This was taken on the road with Slim," Toowoomba-based John Elliott says. "He was doing concerts at night, and we would try and take pictures through the day. We were driving near Wangaratta and I saw this beautiful old shed. I honked, went in, looked around, and there was a farmer on his back under a truck. He was fixing the truck. I said 'hello!' He didn't get out from under the truck, and I said 'I'm a photographer, I've got Slim Dusty in the car, would you mind if I took a few pictures of him against your shed?' He said 'yeah mate, help yourself.' I'm sure he never realised I was telling the truth! I hope he got to see that picture one day."

column1: Through a local lens
column5: "I was a bit embarrassed when they called the exhibition 'Icons on Icons'," says John Elliott. "It put a bit of pressure on me! One shot that came to mind, probably my most famous picture, is a really beautiful snapshot of Dame Edna and Slim Dusty. I took it in 1992 backstage at a concert in the Kimberly. It was really just two mates hanging out. I had a flash on my camera and went 'click'. I think I took three or four frames, and I knew when I clicked the camera it was a really important image. Years later, I read they were going to open a National Portrait gallery in Canberra. I didn't know where the picture was, but I called the director and said 'I've got a shot you need for your gallery'. It took me six months to find it. They bought it before the gallery opened, and used it on the invite for the opening. And when you drive into the National Portrait Gallery now, I snuck in to have a look recently, there's a 12 metre version of it as you drive into the carpark! So it's nice to have a really beautiful print of that photo at the Cobb and Co."
column6: Copyright: Audience submitted | Source: used with permission | Byline: John Elliott

column1: A roadtrip in Winton with Mystery Road film director Ivan Sen
column5: Ivan Sen returns to one of his favourite locations in Mystery Road, about five kilometres south of the Winton township. “I think it’s the variation in the landscape which initially attracted me, if I really think about it I don’t think I’ve seen such a varied landscape in the world,” he says. “A great thing about Winton is accessing that vast landscape very quickly... you don’t have to go very far from town to get that vastness.”

column1: Prized megafauna skull on display
column5: Local farmer, and amateur palaeontologist, Ian Sobbe, says he received a call from the Cobb and Co museum when the fossil was discovered. He says this Diprotodon is "probably the largest, and best preserved, skull we've found on the Darling Downs. It’s significant in terms of the size, and from the quality of preservation that's allowed us to see features we’ve never seen in other skulls previously."

column1: The Shades of November
column5: By 6 September 1999, an estimated 1500 people had taken refuge in the church and compound to escape violence in the district. In the early afternoon, militia and paramilitary forces surrounded the church and began to attack those inside. Among the first casualties were three Catholic priests who were shot or stabbed to death when they tried to intervene. Grenades were thrown and automatic weapons fired through the doors and windows. The church was then set on fire and people trying to flee the burning building were shot or hacked down with machetes. It is believed that as many as 200 people were killed in the space of just a few hours.

column1: Ballets Russes competition photo gallery
column5: My brother, David, and I are dressed in fancy dress for a function at school. It was my last year in Infants School before I went on to Primary School. My mother had made both our outfits. She wasn't a particularly good sewer but I think she has done a pretty good job. I was supposed to be Little Bo Peep, but I seem to have lost my sheep. My outfit was made completely out of crepe paper and Mum had gone to a great deal of trouble in making the hooped skirt and pantaloons. I recall I hated the outfit and didn't want to wear it and much preferred David's Superman costume. It brings back fond memories as my Mum died in 2009 and I miss her greatly. We used this photo in a collage that we put together for her 90th birthday.
